          youth: "Prayer is a battle - the Catechism actually uses that word. Some people say prayer is a waste of time or just talking to yourself; and even when we believe, we face distraction, dryness (when prayer feels empty and God seems absent), and acedia, a kind of spiritual laziness that whispers 'skip it today.' The fix for distraction is not force but humility: notice where your heart ran off to, and turn it back. Dryness is not failure; it can be the moment when faith is most real, clinging to Jesus without any warm feelings. And when prayer seems unanswered, ask: am I treating God like a vending machine, or do I trust him as a Father who knows what I truly need? Jesus told a parable precisely so that we would 'always pray and not lose heart' (Luke 18:1). On the night before he died, in John 17, he prayed for you by name, as it were - and his prayer holds yours.",
          adult: "The Catechism is candid: 'prayer is a battle' against ourselves and against the tempter, who does all he can to turn us away from prayer (CCC 2725). We must contend with erroneous notions - prayer reduced to a psychological activity or an escape from life - and with the mentality that values only production and profit, for which prayer is 'useless' (CCC 2726-2727). Within prayer itself, the common difficulties are distraction, which reveals what our heart is attached to and calls for a humble turning back to the Lord, and dryness, when the heart feels separated from God and finds no taste in prayer; dryness lived in faith is a sharing in Christ's agony and tomb, and 'the grain of wheat that dies bears much fruit' (CCC 2729-2731). The chief temptations are lack of faith and acedia, a form of spiritual sloth arising from lax ascetical practice and carelessness of heart (CCC 2732-2733). When prayer seems unheard, the Catechism asks whether we are using God as a means or seeking him as the Father who gives the Holy Spirit, the true Gift containing all others; we must pray with filial trust, in the name of Jesus, and with a will conformed to his (CCC 2734-2741). Perseverance in love is possible because it is always possible to pray, prayer is a vital necessity, and prayer and Christian life are inseparable (CCC 2742-2745). The unit closes with the prayer of the hour of Jesus, his 'priestly' prayer in John 17, which embraces the whole economy of creation and salvation and remains his prayer for us always, teaching us that his intercession carries our own weak prayer (CCC 2746-2751, 2758)."
